column2: each of them gets N identical-looking blocks of wood with masses between 0.0kg and 1.0kg (exclusive). All of the blocks have different weights. There are lots of games they could play with those blocks
column3: but they usually play something they call War. Here is how War works:\n \n # Each player weighs each of his or her own blocks
column4: so each player knows the weights of all of his or her own blocks
column5: but not the weights of the other player's blocks.\n # They repeat the following process N times:\n # Naomi chooses one of her own blocks
column6: with mass ChosenNaomi.\n # Naomi tells Ken the mass of the block she chose.\n # Ken chooses one of his own blocks

column8: and the person whose block is heavier gets one point.\n # Both blocks are destroyed in a fire.\n # Naomi has realized three things about War. First
column9: she has realized that she loses a lot. Second
column10: she has realized that there is a unique strategy that Ken can follow to maximize his points without assuming anything about Naomi's strategy
column11: and that Ken always uses it. Third
column12: she has realized that she hates to lose. Naomi has decided that instead of playing War
column13: she will play a game she calls Deceitful War. The great thing about Deceitful War is that Ken will think they're playing War!\n \n # Here is how Deceitful War works
column14: with differences between Deceitful War and War in bold:\n \n # Each player weighs each of his or her own blocks. Naomi also weighs Ken's blocks while he isn't looking
column15: so Naomi knows the weights of all blocks and Ken only knows the weights of his own blocks.\n # They repeat the following process N times:\n # Naomi chooses one of her own blocks

column23: and what mass to tell Ken

column25: she must make decisions so that:\n \n # ChosenNaomi > ChosenKen if
column28: and\n # ToldNaomi is not equal to the mass of any of Ken's blocks
column29: because he knows that isn't possible.\n # It might seem like Naomi won't win any extra points by being deceitful
column30: because Ken might discover that she wasn't playing War; but Naomi knows Ken thinks both players are playing War
column31: and she knows what he knows
column32: and she knows Ken will always follow his unique optimal strategy for War

 def best(total):
     """Return the best possible score for the given `total`.  Assume
     the total is computed by summing exactly three scores (each in the
     interval of 0 to 10 inclusive) and no score can be 2 points apart
     from another.
     
     Arguments:
     - `total`:
     """
     m = total % 3

         b = 10
